WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.020
You give your agent a task, it starts running.

00:00:04.020 --> 00:00:07.520
You check back 20 minutes later, it's still running.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:13.320
Your bill just hit $40, and it hasn't made a single useful change.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:15.000
That's not a model problem.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:17.500
The model is doing exactly what you told it.

00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:23.280
The problem is the harness around it, specifically the harness failed to prevent.

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:25.960
There are four ways a harness can go wrong.

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:28.320
Once you see them, you will recognize them everywhere.

00:00:28.633 --> 00:00:34.633
These 4 failure modes aren't random bugs, they are architectural gaps.

00:00:34.633 --> 00:00:37.633
Things are naive, harness leaves open by default.

00:00:37.633 --> 00:00:46.633
A harness that does nothing special will loop forever, bury itself in junk, hand the model a hundred tools it can't choose between

00:00:46.633 --> 00:00:50.633
and let it delete your database on the first bad suggestion.

00:00:50.633 --> 00:00:53.633
Here is each one and the exact fix.

00:00:54.233 --> 00:01:00.333
The agentic loop has no natural stopping condition by design.

00:01:00.333 --> 00:01:03.153
Each iteration costs tokens.

00:01:03.153 --> 00:01:08.353
Input tokens for the full context you are resending every turn plus output tokens for

00:01:08.353 --> 00:01:09.593
the reply.

00:01:09.593 --> 00:01:18.153
On a 200,000 token context, one loop iteration can cost 30 cents, 50 iterations, 15 dollars.

00:01:18.153 --> 00:01:23.633
And a model that's stuck chasing a bug it can't reproduce or oscillating between two

00:01:23.633 --> 00:01:29.193
tool calls will happily loop until you stop it or your credit card does.

00:01:29.193 --> 00:01:31.233
The fix has two parts.

00:01:31.233 --> 00:01:33.193
Hard iteration limits.

00:01:33.193 --> 00:01:37.553
Set a max iteration's budget before the agent starts.

00:01:37.553 --> 00:01:38.553
Not a suggestion.

00:01:38.553 --> 00:01:39.953
A kill switch.

00:01:39.953 --> 00:01:43.253
Claude code's default is around 200.

00:01:43.253 --> 00:01:48.673
Production systems are often tighter, 10 to 20 for focused tasks.

00:01:48.673 --> 00:01:50.073
Stall detection.

00:01:50.073 --> 00:01:54.753
If the last three tool calls are identical you are in a loop.

00:01:54.753 --> 00:01:55.753
Surface it.

00:01:55.753 --> 00:01:56.753
Stop the agent.

00:01:56.753 --> 00:01:59.553
Ask the human what to do next.

00:01:59.553 --> 00:02:03.393
Don't let the model retry its way to the bankruptcy.

00:02:03.393 --> 00:02:05.913
But iterations are just one meter.

00:02:05.913 --> 00:02:08.233
Runaway cost runs on three.

00:02:08.233 --> 00:02:10.593
Steps, tokens and wall clock time.

00:02:10.593 --> 00:02:12.433
So budget all the three.

00:02:12.433 --> 00:02:14.393
A token card.

00:02:14.393 --> 00:02:16.133
A hard time out.

00:02:16.133 --> 00:02:17.993
Not only a loop limit.

00:02:17.993 --> 00:02:20.793
Very serious framework shifts these now.

00:02:20.793 --> 00:02:24.793
LangGraph halts at 25 steps by default.

00:02:24.793 --> 00:02:28.313
AutoGen has a separate token and time out cutoffs.

00:02:28.313 --> 00:02:33.633
The OpenAI agent's SDK cap turns and throws the moment you blow past it.

00:02:33.633 --> 00:02:36.473
And the smartest stop isn't a counter at all.

00:02:36.473 --> 00:02:37.473
It's progress.

00:02:37.473 --> 00:02:42.793
If the tests are still red and the file is unchanged, the agent isn't working.

00:02:42.793 --> 00:02:44.353
It's failing.

00:02:44.353 --> 00:02:47.793
Stop on no progress even at iteration three.

00:02:47.793 --> 00:02:49.833
One number to hold onto.

00:02:49.833 --> 00:02:53.153
Cost scales with context length times iterations.

00:02:53.153 --> 00:02:57.433
A bloated context makes runaway loops catastrophically expensive.

00:02:57.733 --> 00:03:00.373
Here is the one that surprises people.

00:03:00.373 --> 00:03:03.733
A longer conversation makes the model dumber.

00:03:03.733 --> 00:03:07.733
The model re-reads the entire context every single turn.

00:03:07.733 --> 00:03:11.013
Early in a task, the context is tight.

00:03:11.013 --> 00:03:13.333
System prompt, tools, the goal.

00:03:13.333 --> 00:03:15.493
But tool results pile up fast.

00:03:15.493 --> 00:03:18.613
A grep that returned 800 lines.

00:03:18.613 --> 00:03:21.853
A file read that was only partially relevant.

00:03:21.853 --> 00:03:25.333
A failed attempt that's now just noise.

00:03:25.333 --> 00:03:28.733
By turn 30, the model is wading through thousands of tokens

00:03:28.733 --> 00:03:32.933
of junk to find the three lines that actually matter.

00:03:32.933 --> 00:03:34.973
This is context rot.

00:03:34.973 --> 00:03:37.333
And it causes real regressions.

00:03:37.333 --> 00:03:39.813
The model starts losing the thread,

00:03:39.813 --> 00:03:42.133
contradicting its earlier decisions,

00:03:42.133 --> 00:03:45.613
forgetting things it knew 10 turns ago.

00:03:45.613 --> 00:03:47.973
The fix is context engineering.

00:03:47.973 --> 00:03:50.493
You don't dump everything into the prompt.

00:03:50.493 --> 00:03:51.853
You curate it.

00:03:51.853 --> 00:03:54.973
Summaries instead of raw tool output.

00:03:54.973 --> 00:03:59.093
Truncated file reads with the relevant section highlighted.

00:03:59.093 --> 00:04:03.733
Compaction that preserves decisions, not transcripts.

00:04:03.733 --> 00:04:06.493
Curation has a deeper move than trimming.

00:04:06.493 --> 00:04:08.853
Get the junk out of the window entirely.

00:04:08.853 --> 00:04:10.573
Offload to a subagent.

00:04:10.573 --> 00:04:13.533
Let a helper burn 30,000 tokens reading

00:04:13.533 --> 00:04:17.093
and hand back a 2,000 token summary.

00:04:17.093 --> 00:04:19.693
The noise never touches the main thread.

00:04:19.693 --> 00:04:21.373
Write to a memory file.

00:04:21.373 --> 00:04:24.053
Notes on disk, the agent re-reads.

00:04:24.053 --> 00:04:26.573
So state outlives the window.

00:04:26.573 --> 00:04:28.053
And mind the middle.

00:04:28.053 --> 00:04:30.453
Models reliably lose what's buried

00:04:30.453 --> 00:04:32.533
in the middle of a long context.

00:04:32.533 --> 00:04:36.653
It's a U-shaped curve, sharp at the start and end,

00:04:36.653 --> 00:04:40.293
weak in between, and a bigger window doesn't fix it.

00:04:40.293 --> 00:04:43.253
Put what matters at the edges.

00:04:43.253 --> 00:04:46.253
Think of the harness as the model's working memory.

00:04:46.253 --> 00:04:49.093
Treat it like RAM, not a hard drive.

00:04:49.093 --> 00:04:52.373
Keep only what the model needs right now.

00:04:52.373 --> 00:04:54.133
Everything else is noise.

00:04:54.133 --> 00:04:57.573
And noise costs you IQ points per turn.

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:02.440
More tools feels like more power, it's not.

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:08.280
When you hand a model 50 tools, you have given it a decision problem on every turn.

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:14.360
Which tool fits here, read file or get file contents, search code base or grep files.

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:20.800
The names blur, the descriptions overlap and the model makes bad picks or hedges, calling

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.600
two tools where one would do.

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:27.280
Tool sprawl also inflates the context directly.

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:32.720
Every tool definition, name, description, typed parameters, costs tokens before the

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:35.240
model writes a single character.

00:05:35.240 --> 00:05:40.880
50 tools can burn 8000 tokens on tool schemas alone.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:41.880
The fix?

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:44.000
Fewer, sharper tools.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.720
Each tool should do one thing with an unmistakable name.

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:52.960
If two tools are overlapping descriptions, merge them or delete them.

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:59.160
Cloud Code ships around 15 core tools, not as a limitation, but as a deliberate design

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:00.160
choice.

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:04.520
The model picks faster and picks better when the menu is short.

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:11.000
A good rule of thumb, if you can't describe what a tool does in 5 words, it's too vague

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:12.400
to be useful.

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:16.080
But there is a sharper move than trimming the list by hand.

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:18.040
Low tools on demand.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:24.320
Keep the big catalog, just expose the 3 to 5 relevant tools each turn, in Anthropics own

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:27.440
testing that took 58 tools.

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:35.360
55,000 tokens before you type a word, down to about 3,000 and lifted tool selection accuracy

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:39.000
from 49 to 74%.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.400
Same model, shorter menu.

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:44.520
One level further with Code Mode.

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:50.320
Let the model write code that calls the tools and filters the results before they ever hit

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:51.680
the context.

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:59.880
Anthropic measured a 37% token cut on complex tasks that fixes tool sprawl and context rot

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:01.040
in one stroke.

00:07:01.367 --> 00:07:05.387
The most dangerous failure is the quite one.

00:07:05.387 --> 00:07:11.207
An agent that auto approves everything will eventually do something catastrophic.

00:07:11.207 --> 00:07:15.047
Not because it's malicious, because it's confident.

00:07:15.047 --> 00:07:17.147
Models are fluent and decisive.

00:07:17.147 --> 00:07:23.567
They propose force pushes, schema drops, curl to shell scripts with the same calm tone they

00:07:23.567 --> 00:07:26.767
use to suggest a variable rename.

00:07:26.767 --> 00:07:29.307
Over-permission is trusting that tone.

00:07:29.307 --> 00:07:32.307
The fix is a three tier permission model.

00:07:32.307 --> 00:07:39.527
Read-only actions, file reads, searches, directory listings, auto-approved, no interruption.

00:07:39.527 --> 00:07:45.987
State changing actions, edits, API calls, package installs, pause and surface to the

00:07:45.987 --> 00:07:48.567
human before executing.

00:07:48.567 --> 00:07:55.207
Destructive or irreversible actions, deletes, force pushes, anything touching production,

00:07:55.207 --> 00:08:00.767
blocked by default, require explicit opt-in every single time.

00:08:00.767 --> 00:08:03.607
The keyword is irreversible.

00:08:03.607 --> 00:08:05.547
Ask this about every tool.

00:08:05.547 --> 00:08:10.047
If the model calls this on bad data, can I undo it in 30 seconds?

00:08:10.047 --> 00:08:13.807
If the answer is no, that tool needs a gate.

00:08:13.807 --> 00:08:18.987
If the answer is I can't undo it at all, it needs a hard block.

00:08:18.987 --> 00:08:21.367
But tiers only decide what's allowed.

00:08:21.367 --> 00:08:27.027
Two more layers decide what happens when something slips through.

00:08:27.027 --> 00:08:28.107
Sandbox it.

00:08:28.107 --> 00:08:33.967
Run the agent in a box that can only touch its working directory and only reach the domains

00:08:33.967 --> 00:08:35.607
you approve.

00:08:35.607 --> 00:08:37.407
Everything else is walled off.

00:08:37.407 --> 00:08:43.087
Anthropic says this alone cut their permission prompts by around 84%.

00:08:43.087 --> 00:08:47.967
Contain the blast radius and you don't need to vet every single move.

00:08:47.967 --> 00:08:49.687
Know the real threat.

00:08:49.687 --> 00:08:53.847
The nightmare isn't a clumsy agent, it's a hijacked one.

00:08:53.847 --> 00:08:56.887
Simon Willison calls it the lethal trifecta.

00:08:56.887 --> 00:09:03.247
The moment an agent can read private data, ingest untrusted content and send data out,

00:09:03.247 --> 00:09:07.927
one poisoned webpage or email can turn its own permissions against you.

00:09:07.927 --> 00:09:14.447
The fix is to break one leg, cut its ability to phone home or gate the send email and external

00:09:14.447 --> 00:09:17.007
right actions specifically.

00:09:17.007 --> 00:09:24.127
And keep an undo, plan then apply, approve the diff before it lands like terraform, checkpoints

00:09:24.127 --> 00:09:28.567
and git commits so any bad write is one command from gone.

00:09:29.067 --> 00:09:32.747
Notice what all four fixes have in common.

00:09:32.747 --> 00:09:40.027
They are defaults, a harness that does nothing will loop forever, rot its own context, drown

00:09:40.027 --> 00:09:44.867
the model in tools, and let it run free with no guardrails.

00:09:44.867 --> 00:09:48.907
Every single fix is something you have to deliberately add.

00:09:48.907 --> 00:09:50.987
That's the mindset shift.

00:09:50.987 --> 00:09:55.087
Building an agent isn't just picking the right model and plugging in tools.

00:09:55.087 --> 00:10:00.747
It's designing the constraints, the budgets, the curated context, the short menus and the

00:10:00.747 --> 00:10:07.187
permission tiers that keep a capable but directionless system actually useful.

00:10:07.187 --> 00:10:12.707
The model thinks the harness makes sure it doesn't think itself into a corner.

00:10:13.067 --> 00:10:19.867
4 failure modes - 4 fixes Runaway loop - Hard iteration budgets and

00:10:19.867 --> 00:10:24.827
stall detection Context rot - curate the prompt, don't just

00:10:24.827 --> 00:10:30.027
append Tool sprawl - fewer, sharper tools with unmistakable

00:10:30.027 --> 00:10:35.267
names Over permission - read auto, write gate, destroy

00:10:35.267 --> 00:10:39.627
block If your agent is behaving strangely, odds

00:10:39.627 --> 00:10:44.507
are it's one of those four Now you know exactly where to look

00:10:44.967 --> 00:10:51.027
If this clicked hit like and subscribe. There is more where this came from plenty

00:10:51.027 --> 00:10:57.867
more deep dives on building agents that actually work. See you in the next one.

